					<head>Megilat Ester</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79053644" rend="visible">
						<summary>The book of Esther. </summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79053644">
							<locus from="1r" to="20v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Megilat Ester </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">מגלת אסתר</title>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<extent>20 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>286</height>
										<width>159</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>20 folios (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 3 at the end). Folio 1 is a paper flyleaf. </p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Previously in the form of scroll, now in book-form. </p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="21" writtenLines="21">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>19 columns, first four with vowel-points.</p>
									<p>The letters of שעטנזגץ provided with three tagin. One tag placed on the letters בדהחיק.</p>
									<p>Majuscular letters in verses: 1:6, 9:9, 9:29; minuscular letters in verses: 9:7, 9:9.</p>
									<p>The names of the sons of Haman arranged according to the rule.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Sefardi aquare script of the 15th century. </summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>From the collection of <name type="person" role="owner">Adam Clarke</name> (b. 1762, d. 1832), Wesleyan Methodist minister and scholar: inscribed, folio 1v. </p>
							<p>Folio 1v (paper flyleaf at the beginning of the manuscript): a note of ownership of <name type="person" role="owner">J. Noble Coleman</name>: his bookplate with Latin inscription: recte sed suaviter (inner upper cover). The manuscript was given to him by <name type="person" role="owner">George Pope</name>, having been bought from a bookseller in Bristol.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Brown leather. Gold tooled.</p>
								<p>Spine title: &apos;Esther. Hebrew. Oriental 1087.&apos;</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
